XXIX. Resembling these substances both in name Cardamom. and in the shrub that produces it is cardamomum‚‘² the seeds of which are oblong in shape. It is gathered in Arabia, in the same manner as amomum. It has four varieties: one very green and oily, with sharp corners and awkward to crumble—this is the kind most highly spoken of—the next sort a whitish red, the third shorter and of a colour nearer black, while an inferior kind is mottled and easily friable, and has little scent-—in the true kind the scent ought to be near to that of costus. Cardamomum also grows in the country of the Medes.l> The price of the best sort is 3 denarii a pound.
